attributes.background:
In a democracy, it is the duty of the police to facilitate protest, not to stifle and suppress it. As shown in recent video evidence, police officers:
(i) attacked protesters who posed no physical threat, resulting in severe injury and possibly death;
(ii) pushed protests into confined spaces, inducing overcrowding and increasing tension;
(iii) set their own limits on which protests were and were not allowed;
(iv) concealed their identifying numbers from protest participants, to prevent them from making a complaint to the IPCC.
After the protests, the IPCC did not look into the allegations seriously until independent video evidence forced them to. They did not consult ubiquitous CCTV footage in central London. They placed full responsibility on individual protesters to make complaints, even after it emerged the police had shielded their identification numbers. As yet, the public is not confident that there is sufficient oversight for the police service.
